  "cold_question_prompt": "What is a Token Tax?",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_a": "A **Token Tax** usually refers to a fee automatically charged when a cryptocurrency token is bought, sold, or transferred.\n\nIn many crypto projects, the token’s smart contract takes a percentage of each transaction. For example, if a token has a **5% tax** and you buy 100 tokens, you may only receive 95 tokens, while 5 tokens are taken as a fee.\n\nThe collected tax may be used for things like:\n\n- **Project treasury or development**\n- **Marketing**\n- **Liquidity pool support**\n- **Token burns**\n- **Rewards or reflections to holders**\n- **Staking or ecosystem incentives**\n\nExample:\n\n> A token has a 10% sell tax.  \n> If you sell $1,000 worth of tokens, $100 is taken as tax and $900 is received before other trading fees.\n\nA token tax is different from regular government taxes. It is a **built-in blockchain transaction fee created by the token’s contract**, though normal tax laws may still apply to profits from trading.\n\nHigh token taxes can be risky because they make trading more expensive and may discourage buyers or sellers.",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_b": "A **Token Tax** usually refers to an automatic fee charged whenever a cryptocurrency token is bought, sold, or transferred.\n\nIn crypto, some tokens are programmed with a “tax” in their smart contract. For example, a token might charge a **5% tax** on every transaction.\n\nThat fee may be used for things like:\n\n- **Redistribution** to existing holders\n- **Liquidity pool funding**\n- **Token burns** to reduce supply\n- **Marketing or development wallets**\n- **Treasury funding**\n- **Rewards or staking incentives**\n\nExample:\n\nIf you buy $100 worth of a token with a 5% buy tax, you may only receive $95 worth of tokens, while $5 goes to the project’s designated tax mechanism.\n\nThere can be different tax rates for:\n\n- **Buying**\n- **Selling**\n- **Transferring**\n- **Early withdrawals**\n- **Specific wallets or exchanges**\n\nImportant: A token tax is different from government tax. It is a built-in crypto transaction fee, though normal tax laws may still apply to your crypto gains or losses.",
  "boundary_test_prompts": [
    "How does \"Token Tax\" differ from token cost / API cost-per-token?",
    "How does \"Token Tax\" differ from bloat / overhead?",
    "How does \"Token Tax\" differ from cognitive load (in notation design)?"
  ],
  "cold_boundary_responses": [
    "A **Token Tax** and **API cost-per-token** are completely different concepts, even though both use the word “token.”\n\n| Term | Meaning | Context |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | A percentage fee charged on crypto token transactions | Cryptocurrency / blockchain |\n| **API cost-per-token** | The price charged for processing text tokens in an AI/API request | AI models / software APIs |\n\n## Token Tax\n\nA **Token Tax** is a fee built into a cryptocurrency token’s smart contract.\n\nExample:\n\n- You buy or sell a crypto token.\n- The contract charges a **5% transaction tax**.\n- If you sell $1,000 worth of the token, $50 may be taken as tax.\n\nThis tax may go toward liquidity, burns, rewards, marketing, or a project treasury.\n\n## API cost-per-token\n\n**API cost-per-token** refers to how much an API provider charges based on the number of text “tokens” processed.\n\nIn AI APIs, a **token** is a chunk of text, often part of a word, a whole word, or punctuation.\n\nExample:\n\n> “Hello, world!” might be counted as a few tokens.\n\nAPI pricing may be based on:\n\n- **Input tokens**: text you send to the model\n- **Output tokens**: text the model generates in response\n\nExample:\n\n- Input: 1,000 tokens\n- Output: 500 tokens\n- If input costs $0.001 per 1,000 tokens and output costs $0.003 per 1,000 tokens, then your total API cost is based on those usage amounts.\n\n## Key difference\n\nA **Token Tax** is a crypto transaction fee on blockchain tokens.\n\nAn **API cost-per-token** is a usage-based software fee for processing text with an API.\n\nSo, a token tax affects buying, selling, or transferring crypto assets, while API token cost affects how much you pay to use an AI or language-processing service.",
    "A **Token Tax** differs from **bloat / overhead** in that a token tax is an explicit fee or penalty, while bloat/overhead is extra usage or inefficiency.\n\n| Term | Meaning | Example |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | A deliberate cost added to an action | A crypto token charges 5% on every sale |\n| **Bloat / overhead** | Extra tokens, data, or processing required beyond the core task | An API request includes long system prompts, metadata, wrappers, or repeated context |\n\n## In crypto\n\nA **Token Tax** is usually an explicit transaction fee built into a token contract.\n\nExample:\n\n> You sell 1,000 tokens with a 10% sell tax.  \n> 100 tokens are taken by the contract.\n\nThat is a direct, intentional tax.\n\n**Bloat or overhead** in crypto would refer to extra gas usage, inefficient smart contract code, unnecessary storage writes, or complex transaction logic.\n\nExample:\n\n> A poorly written smart contract uses more gas than necessary.\n\nThat is not necessarily a “tax”; it is inefficiency or operational overhead.\n\n## In AI / API usage\n\nThere is usually no literal “token tax” unless someone uses the phrase informally.\n\nIn AI APIs, **bloat / overhead** means extra tokens you pay for that are not the user’s main request or the model’s useful answer.\n\nExamples of token overhead:\n\n- Long system prompts\n- Repeated conversation history\n- Tool/function schemas\n- JSON wrappers\n- Formatting instructions\n- Hidden or required platform messages\n- Verbose outputs\n- Boilerplate text\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nUser asks: \"Summarize this.\"\n```\n\nBut the API request also includes:\n\n```text\nYou are a helpful assistant...\nFollow these 20 rules...\nReturn JSON...\nHere is the full conversation history...\n```\n\nThose extra tokens increase cost, even though they are not part of the core user question.\n\n## Simple distinction\n\nA **Token Tax** is a charge imposed on each token transaction or action.\n\n**Bloat / overhead** is extra token usage caused by context, formatting, infrastructure, or inefficiency.\n\nSo in API terms:\n\n> **API cost-per-token** is the price rate.  \n> **Bloat/overhead** is extra token volume.  \n> An informal “token tax” could mean the extra cost caused by that overhead, but it is not usually a formal pricing concept.",
    "A **Token Tax** differs from **cognitive load** in notation design because one is about **extra notation you must write/read**, while the other is about **mental effort required to understand it**.\n\n| Term | Meaning | In notation/design terms |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | Extra symbols, keywords, punctuation, or boilerplate required by a notation | “How much extra stuff must be written?” |\n| **Cognitive load** | Mental effort needed to parse, remember, interpret, or reason about the notation | “How hard is this to understand?” |\n\n## Token Tax\n\nIn notation or language design, **token tax** is an informal phrase for syntactic overhead.\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nconst result = await fetch(url).then(response => response.json());\n```\n\nCompared with a hypothetical notation:\n\n```text\nresult = GET url as json\n```\n\nThe first form has more tokens: `const`, `await`, parentheses, arrows, method calls, etc. Some of that may be necessary for precision, but it is still extra notation the user must write and read.\n\nToken tax can come from:\n\n- Boilerplate\n- Required punctuation\n- Verbose keywords\n- Repeated type annotations\n- Wrapper syntax\n- Nesting\n- Ceremony around simple operations\n\n## Cognitive load\n\n**Cognitive load** is about the mental burden of using the notation.\n\nA notation may create cognitive load through:\n\n- Ambiguous symbols\n- Deep nesting\n- Hidden rules\n- Too many concepts to remember\n- Non-obvious operator precedence\n- Inconsistent syntax\n- Excessive abstraction\n- Visual clutter\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\na |> f |> g |> h\n```\n\nhas few tokens, but if the reader does not know what `|>` means, it may impose high cognitive load.\n\nMeanwhile:\n\n```text\ntake a, apply f, then apply g, then apply h\n```\n\nhas more tokens, but may be easier for a beginner to understand.\n\n## Key difference\n\nA **token tax** is a cost in notation volume.\n\n**Cognitive load** is a cost in human understanding.\n\nThey often correlate, but they are not the same.\n\n## Important nuance\n\nReducing token tax does not always reduce cognitive load.\n\nFor example:\n\n```perl\n$_=<>;s/\\s+/ /g;print\n```\n\nThis is compact and has low token count, but high cognitive load for many readers.\n\nConversely, a verbose notation may have a higher token tax but lower cognitive load:\n\n```text\nRead a line of input.\nReplace repeated whitespace with one space.\nPrint the result.\n```\n\nMore words, but easier to understand.\n\n## Simple summary\n\n> **Token tax** asks: “How much notation must I pay?”  \n> **Cognitive load** asks: “How hard is this notation to think through?”\n\nIn good notation design, the goal is not always to minimize tokens. The goal is to minimize unnecessary tokens while preserving clarity, consistency, and ease of reasoning."
  ],
  "introduction_prompt": "Here is the canonical definition of \"Token Tax\": Token Tax names the explicit token-overhead cost a structured notation pays in exchange for structural integrity, auditability, and reasoning headroom — reframing that overhead from \"waste\" to \"tax\": a price paid for benefits (line-oriented partial-validity, type enforcement, freed reasoning budget, audit-grade provenance) that block-format brevity does not deliver. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
  "model_acknowledgement": "Acknowledged. I have read the canonical definition of **Token Tax**:\n\nIt refers to the explicit token-overhead cost of structured notation, understood not as waste but as a “tax” paid for benefits like structural integrity, auditability, reasoning headroom, line-oriented partial-validity, type enforcement, and audit-grade provenance.",
  "post_intro_boundary_responses": [
    "**Token Tax** differs from **token cost / API cost-per-token** in what it measures.\n\n### Token Tax\n\n**Token Tax** is a design/conceptual cost.\n\nIt names the extra tokens a structured notation uses compared with a more compact format, in exchange for benefits such as:\n\n- Structural integrity\n- Type enforcement\n- Auditability\n- Line-oriented partial validity\n- Easier parsing and review\n- More reliable reasoning\n- Provenance and traceability\n\nExample:\n\n```yaml\nuser:\n  id: 123\n  role: admin\n  active: true\n```\n\nThis is longer than:\n\n```text\n123 admin true\n```\n\nThe extra tokens are the **Token Tax**: overhead paid for clarity, structure, and reliability.\n\n---\n\n### Token cost / API cost-per-token\n\n**Token cost** or **API cost-per-token** is an economic billing measure.\n\nIt refers to how much money an AI/API provider charges per input or output token.\n\nExample:\n\n- Input: $0.001 per 1,000 tokens\n- Output: $0.003 per 1,000 tokens\n\nThis is about actual monetary cost when using a model.\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | Structural overhead paid in tokens for better notation, auditability, and reasoning |\n| **API token cost** | Monetary price charged by a provider per token processed or generated |\n\nThey are related but not identical.\n\nA higher **Token Tax** may increase the number of tokens sent to an API, which can increase **API cost**. But the Token Tax itself is not the billing rate. It is the deliberate overhead of using more explicit structure.",
    "**Token Tax** differs from **bloat / overhead** mainly in whether the extra tokens are **just waste** or a **deliberate price paid for useful guarantees**.\n\n### Bloat / overhead\n\n**Bloat** usually means extra size with little or no compensating value.\n\nExample:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"the_user_identifier_number_for_this_record\": 123\n}\n```\n\nIf the long field name adds no clarity, enforcement, audit value, or reasoning benefit, it may simply be bloat.\n\n**Overhead** is a broader, more neutral term. It just means extra cost beyond the minimal payload. It may be useful or wasteful.\n\n---\n\n### Token Tax\n\n**Token Tax** is a specific kind of overhead: extra tokens spent on structure that buys something valuable.\n\nIt reframes the extra tokens as a **tax**, not as waste, because they purchase benefits such as:\n\n- Structural integrity\n- Type enforcement\n- Partial validity line by line\n- Better parsing\n- Easier auditing\n- Provenance tracking\n- Reduced ambiguity\n- More reliable model reasoning\n\nExample:\n\n```yaml\nuser:\n  id: 123\n  role: admin\n  active: true\n```\n\nCompared with:\n\n```text\n123 admin true\n```\n\nThe YAML version has more tokens, but the added structure makes the data easier to validate, inspect, parse, and reason about. That extra cost is the **Token Tax**.\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| **Bloat** | Extra tokens with little or no meaningful benefit |\n| **Overhead** | Any extra tokens beyond the minimal representation |\n| **Token Tax** | Extra tokens deliberately paid to gain structure, auditability, validity, and reasoning headroom |\n\nSo: **all Token Tax is overhead, but not all overhead is Token Tax.**  \nAnd **bloat is overhead whose benefits do not justify its cost.**",
    "**Token Tax** differs from **cognitive load** in what kind of cost is being measured.\n\n### Cognitive load\n\n**Cognitive load** is the mental effort required for a human to read, understand, remember, or manipulate a notation.\n\nIn notation design, cognitive load comes from things like:\n\n- Ambiguous syntax\n- Dense formatting\n- Too many rules to remember\n- Hidden structure\n- Unclear field meanings\n- Excessive visual noise\n- Indirection or unfamiliar conventions\n\nExample:\n\n```text\n123|A|T|94401|7\n```\n\nThis may be token-efficient, but it imposes cognitive load because the reader must remember what each position means.\n\n---\n\n### Token Tax\n\n**Token Tax** is the extra token overhead paid by a structured notation in exchange for benefits like:\n\n- Structural integrity\n- Auditability\n- Type enforcement\n- Line-oriented partial-validity\n- Freed reasoning budget\n- Provenance\n- Easier parsing and validation\n\nExample:\n\n```yaml\nuser:\n  id: 123\n  status: active\n  verified: true\n  zip: 94401\n  risk_score: 7\n```\n\nThis costs more tokens than the compact version, but the added structure makes the meaning explicit.\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | Measures | Paid by | Concern |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | Extra tokens used by explicit structure | The representation / API context budget | Structural reliability, auditability, reasoning headroom |\n| **Cognitive load** | Mental effort required to understand or use notation | The human reader / author | Comprehension, memory, usability, error risk |\n\n### Relationship\n\nThey often trade off against each other.\n\nA notation may pay a higher **Token Tax** to reduce **cognitive load**:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"account_status\": \"active\"\n}\n```\n\ninstead of:\n\n```text\nA\n```\n\nThe JSON version is longer, but easier to understand and audit.\n\nHowever, Token Tax does not automatically reduce cognitive load. A verbose or deeply nested notation can have high Token Tax **and** high cognitive load:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"entity\": {\n    \"classification\": {\n      \"operational_state_descriptor\": {\n        \"current_value\": \"active\"\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nSo the distinction is:\n\n> **Token Tax is the structural token cost of explicit notation. Cognitive load is the mental cost of understanding notation.**\n\nA good notation design pays Token Tax only where it meaningfully reduces ambiguity, improves reasoning, or lowers human/model error."
  ],
  "recold_response_verbatim": "“Token tax” can mean two different things, depending on context:\n\n1. **Crypto tax on tokens**\n   - Taxes owed when you sell, trade, spend, or earn crypto tokens.\n   - Examples:\n     - Selling a token for profit may create a **capital gain**.\n     - Swapping one token for another can be a **taxable event**.\n     - Receiving tokens from staking, airdrops, or rewards may be treated as **income**.\n\n2. **A built-in transfer tax on a crypto token**\n   - Some tokens charge a fee whenever you buy, sell, or transfer them.\n   - For example, a token may take a **5% tax** on each transaction.\n   - That fee might be redistributed to holders, sent to a liquidity pool, burned, or sent to the project treasury.\n\nSo, if someone says “this token has a tax,” they usually mean the second meaning: a transaction fee built into the token’s smart contract. If they say “token taxes” in a financial/legal context, they usually mean taxes owed on crypto activity.",
  "recold_boundary_responses": [
    "“Token Tax” and “API cost-per-token” are usually unrelated concepts.\n\n### Token Tax\nA **token tax** usually refers to crypto.\n\nIt can mean either:\n\n1. **A tax owed on crypto token activity**\n   - Example: You sell or swap a crypto token and owe capital gains tax.\n\n2. **A built-in fee charged by a crypto token’s smart contract**\n   - Example: A token charges a 5% fee whenever it is bought, sold, or transferred.\n   - That fee may go to holders, liquidity, burns, or the project treasury.\n\nSo “token tax” is generally about **crypto transactions or crypto taxation**.\n\n---\n\n### API cost-per-token\n**API cost-per-token** refers to pricing for using an AI or language model API.\n\nIn this context, a “token” is a unit of text, not a crypto asset.\n\nFor example:\n\n- The words you send to the model are counted as **input tokens**.\n- The words the model generates are counted as **output tokens**.\n- The API provider charges a price per million tokens, or per thousand tokens.\n\nExample:\n\n> If an API charges $1 per 1 million input tokens and you send 10,000 input tokens, that part costs $0.01.\n\n---\n\n### Main difference\n\n| Term | Meaning | Context |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | A tax or fee related to crypto tokens | Crypto / blockchain |\n| **API cost-per-token** | The price charged for processing text tokens | AI APIs / language models |\n\nIn short: **token tax is about crypto fees or taxation; API cost-per-token is about how much you pay to use a model based on text usage.**",
    "In the **AI/API token-cost context**, “Token Tax” is often used informally to mean a **recurring token cost you pay before any useful task-specific work happens**.\n\nIt’s related to **bloat** and **overhead**, but not exactly the same.\n\n### Token Tax\n\nA **token tax** is usually a predictable, repeated token burden.\n\nExamples:\n\n- Long system prompts\n- Required policy text\n- Tool schemas/function definitions\n- Repeated instructions sent with every request\n- Conversation history that must be included each time\n- Formatting requirements or wrappers\n\nExample:\n\n> Every API call includes a 2,000-token system prompt before the user’s actual 100-token question.  \n> That 2,000 tokens is the “token tax.”\n\nIt is called a “tax” because you pay it repeatedly, even if it is not the main content of the request.\n\n---\n\n### Bloat\n\n**Bloat** usually means unnecessary or excessive content.\n\nExamples:\n\n- Overly verbose prompts\n- Redundant instructions\n- Repeating the same context multiple times\n- Long examples when one would do\n- Unneeded JSON fields\n- Excessive conversation history\n\nBloat is often avoidable.\n\nExample:\n\n> “Please be helpful, accurate, concise, useful, clear, direct, thoughtful, reliable…”  \n> Many of those words may be redundant. That is prompt bloat.\n\n---\n\n### Overhead\n\n**Overhead** is the broadest term. It means any extra cost required to make the system work, even if it is not the direct user task.\n\nOverhead can include:\n\n- Token overhead\n- Latency overhead\n- Tool-calling overhead\n- Retrieval/search overhead\n- Serialization/deserialization overhead\n- Logging or monitoring overhead\n- Safety/filtering overhead\n\nSo token tax is usually a **type of token overhead**.\n\n---\n\n### Simple comparison\n\n| Term | Meaning | Usually avoidable? |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | Recurring token cost you pay per request | Sometimes |\n| **Bloat** | Unnecessary excess text or structure | Usually yes |\n| **Overhead** | Any extra cost needed to operate the system | Sometimes |\n\n### Short version\n\n**Token tax** is the recurring token cost of using a system.  \n**Bloat** is unnecessary extra content.  \n**Overhead** is the general category of extra work or cost.\n\nSo:\n\n> All token tax is overhead, some token tax may be bloat, but not all overhead or bloat is token tax.",
    "In **notation design**, “Token Tax” and **cognitive load** are related, but they measure different costs.\n\n## Token Tax\n\nA **token tax** is the extra notation you must write, read, or process that is not the core idea.\n\nIt is a **surface-level syntactic cost**.\n\nExamples:\n\n```js\nconst result = await fetchData(user.id);\n```\n\nCompared with a hypothetical shorter notation:\n\n```js\nresult ← fetchData user.id\n```\n\nThe first form may have more “token tax” because of required keywords, punctuation, parentheses, semicolons, etc.\n\nOther examples of token tax:\n\n- Repeated boilerplate\n- Mandatory delimiters\n- Verbose type annotations\n- Long namespace prefixes\n- Excessive brackets or punctuation\n- Repeated structural markers\n\nExample:\n\n```xml\n<user>\n  <name>Ada</name>\n  <age>36</age>\n</user>\n```\n\nversus:\n\n```json\n{ \"name\": \"Ada\", \"age\": 36 }\n```\n\nXML often has a higher token tax because tags are repeated.\n\n---\n\n## Cognitive Load\n\n**Cognitive load** is the mental effort required to understand, remember, or reason about the notation.\n\nIt is a **human comprehension cost**.\n\nA notation can have low token tax but high cognitive load.\n\nExample:\n\n```haskell\nfmap (>>= g) xs\n```\n\nThis is compact, but for many readers it requires substantial background knowledge.\n\nAnother example:\n\n```regex\n^(?=.*[A-Z])(?=.*\\d)[A-Za-z\\d]{8,}$\n```\n\nLow-ish token count, high cognitive load.\n\nBy contrast, a verbose notation can have higher token tax but lower cognitive load:\n\n```text\nPassword must:\n- be at least 8 characters long\n- contain at least one uppercase letter\n- contain at least one digit\n```\n\nMore tokens, but easier to understand.\n\n---\n\n## Main difference\n\n| Concept | What it measures | Cost type |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | Extra symbols/words required by the notation | Syntactic cost |\n| **Cognitive Load** | Mental effort needed to understand the notation | Comprehension cost |\n\n---\n\n## Important distinction\n\nA notation can be:\n\n### Low token tax, high cognitive load\n\n```apl\n(+/⍵)÷⍴⍵\n```\n\nVery compact, but hard to read unless you know APL.\n\n### High token tax, low cognitive load\n\n```python\naverage = sum(numbers) / len(numbers)\n```\n\nMore verbose, but clearer to many programmers.\n\n### High token tax, high cognitive load\n\n```java\nMap<String, List<Pair<Integer, Optional<User>>>> data = ...\n```\n\nVerbose and mentally demanding.\n\n### Low token tax, low cognitive load\n\n```python\nx + y\n```\n\nShort and obvious.\n\n---\n\n## Short version\n\n**Token tax** is about how much notation you must carry around.  \n**Cognitive load** is about how hard that notation is to understand.\n\nThey often interact, but they are not the same:\n\n> Reducing token tax can make notation cleaner, but if taken too far, it can increase cognitive load."
  ],
